**__ROS-Messages__**

We will take a look at a few commands which will help us to understand ROS-Messages.
Open a ROS-Network and connect MATLAB to it.
Then execute:

>{{html}}<font size="2">rostopic list</font>{{/html}}

You will see a list of the available or active ROS-Topics
To find out which Node is the Publisher and which have subscribed to the Topics execute:

>{{html}}<font size="2">rostopic info /{TOPIC}</font>{{/html}}

For example:

>{{html}}<font size="2">rostopic info /rosout</font>{{/html}}

The output will look similar to this:

>{{html}}<font size="2">Type: rosgraph_msgs/Log</font>{{/html}}
>{{html}}<font size="2"> </font>{{/html}}
>{{html}}<font size="2">Publishers:</font>{{/html}}
>{{html}}<font size="2">* /matlab_global_node_10184 (http://172.16.10.115:1874/)</font>{{/html}}
>{{html}}<font size="2"> </font>{{/html}}
>{{html}}<font size="2">Subscribers:</font>{{/html}}
>{{html}}<font size="2">* /rosout (http://user-VirtualBox:43057/)</font>{{/html}}

As you can see there is also an info about the messagetype of the Topic.
In this case it's "rosgraph_msgs/Log". To learn more about the architecture of a rosmessage you can use the folowing command:

>{{html}}<font size="2">rosmessage('{Message Type}')</font>{{/html}}

e.g.

>{{html}}<font size="2">rosmessage('sensor_msgs/Image')</font>{{/html}}

With the output:

>{{html}}<font size="2">    MessageType: 'sensor_msgs/Image'</font>{{/html}}
>{{html}}<font size="2">         Header: [1×1 Header]</font>{{/html}}
>{{html}}<font size="2">         Height: 0</font>{{/html}}
>{{html}}<font size="2">          Width: 0</font>{{/html}}
>{{html}}<font size="2">       Encoding: ''</font>{{/html}}
>{{html}}<font size="2">    IsBigendian: 0</font>{{/html}}
>{{html}}<font size="2">           Step: 0</font>{{/html}}
>{{html}}<font size="2">           Data: [0×1 uint8]</font>{{/html}}

We see the information this specific Type of rosmessage contains an can use the information when we create our own ROS-message. In this example it's a sensor_msgs/Image.

If you work with ROS-messages it's good to take a look at the Documentation of the Messagetype and Package:
http://wiki.ros.org/common_msgs?distro=kinetic
http://wiki.ros.org/std_msgs

----

If you want to learn more about how to handle ROS-messages in MATLAB itself you can perform the following two tutorials:
https://de.mathworks.com/help/robotics/examples/work-with-basic-ros-messages.html
https://de.mathworks.com/help/robotics/examples/work-with-specialized-ros-messages.html
